<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-156-582  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 156 582.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer  Feb 1990 v23 n2 p56(10).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Process groups and group communications: classifications andrequirements.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Liang, Luping; Chanson, Samuel T.; Neufeld, Gerald W.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A classification framework is developed for distributedapplications that run on integrated group communication systems tofacilitate the design of such systems.andP;  Group communication is anoperating system-level abstraction consisting of groups,composites of 'objects sharing common application semantics,' and,typically, a multicast communications strategy.andP;  Process groupsconsist of a set of manager processes affecting application-levelobjects, which consist of sets of variables and operations onthose variables.andP;  Process groups may be data and operationhomogeneous, operation homogeneous only, data homogeneous only,and heterogeneous.andP;  The process can also be classified asdeterministic or nondeterministic, depending upon their externalbehavior.andP;  The differences between the two classes incommunication, naming, reply handling, failure handling, and otherfunctions are discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Systems AnalysisClassification SystemsRequirements AnalysisDistributed SystemsSystem DesignWork Group ComputingModels.andO;Feature:   illustrationcharttable.andO;Caption:   One-to-many, inter- and intragroup, and many-to-manycommunications. (chart)Communication pattern for overlapping groups. (chart)Differences between deterministic and nondeterministic categories.andO;(table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>